.TH "DAEMONIZE" "1" "April 2026" "daemonize 0.1.0"
.SH NAME
daemonize \- run a program as a Unix daemon
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]daemonize\f[R] [\f[I]OPTIONS\f[R]] \f[B]\[en]\f[R]
\f[I]program\f[R] [\f[I]args\f[R]\&...]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[B]daemonize\f[R] runs \f[I]program\f[R] as a Unix daemon, detaching
it from the controlling terminal via the standard double\-fork method.
The parent process waits for the daemon to start successfully before
exiting, so \f[B]daemonize\f[R] can be used reliably in init scripts and
process supervisors.
.PP
The daemonization sequence:
.IP " 1." 4
Creates a notification pipe, then forks.
.IP " 2." 4
Calls \f[B]setsid\f[R](2) to create a new session.
.IP " 3." 4
Forks a second time so the daemon cannot reacquire a controlling
terminal.
.IP " 4." 4
Sets the umask, changes the working directory, and redirects
stdin/stdout/stderr to \f[I]/dev/null\f[R].
.IP " 5." 4
Writes the PID file and acquires the lock file (if configured).
.IP " 6." 4
Resets all signal dispositions to \f[B]SIG_DFL\f[R] and clears the
signal mask.
.IP " 7." 4
Applies environment variables and switches user (if configured).
.IP " 8." 4
Redirects stdout/stderr to files (if configured), after the user switch
so files have correct ownership.
.IP " 9." 4
Closes all inherited file descriptors (except the lock file).
.IP "10." 4
Exec\[cq]s \f[I]program\f[R].
.PP
The parent exits 0 only after the daemon has successfully exec\[cq]d
\f[I]program\f[R].
If any step fails, the parent exits with a non\-zero status and prints a
diagnostic to stderr.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]\-p\f[R], \f[B]\[en]pidfile\f[R] \f[I]path\f[R]
Write the daemon\[cq]s PID to \f[I]path\f[R].
The path must be absolute.
.TP
\f[B]\-c\f[R], \f[B]\[en]chdir\f[R] \f[I]path\f[R]
Change the daemon\[cq]s working directory to \f[I]path\f[R] (default:
\f[B]/\f[R]).
The path must be absolute and refer to an existing directory.
.TP
\f[B]\-m\f[R], \f[B]\[en]umask\f[R] \f[I]mode\f[R]
Set the daemon\[cq]s file creation mask to \f[I]mode\f[R] (octal,
e.g.\ \f[B]022\f[R]).
Default: \f[B]000\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]\-o\f[R], \f[B]\[en]stdout\f[R] \f[I]path\f[R]
Redirect the daemon\[cq]s stdout to \f[I]path\f[R].
The path must be absolute.
If both \f[B]\-o\f[R] and \f[B]\-e\f[R] refer to the same file, the file
is opened once and shared between both streams.
.TP
\f[B]\-e\f[R], \f[B]\[en]stderr\f[R] \f[I]path\f[R]
Redirect the daemon\[cq]s stderr to \f[I]path\f[R].
The path must be absolute.
.TP
\f[B]\-a\f[R], \f[B]\[en]append\f[R]
Open stdout/stderr files in append mode instead of truncating them.
.TP
\f[B]\-l\f[R], \f[B]\[en]lock\f[R] \f[I]path\f[R]
Acquire an exclusive lock on \f[I]path\f[R] using \f[B]flock\f[R](2).
Prevents multiple instances of the same daemon from running
simultaneously.
The lock file is held for the lifetime of the daemon process and
survives across \f[B]exec\f[R](3).
The path must be absolute.
.TP
\f[B]\-E\f[R], \f[B]\[en]env\f[R] \f[I]name\f[R]=\f[I]value\f[R]
Set environment variable \f[I]name\f[R] to \f[I]value\f[R] in the
daemon.
May be specified multiple times.
If \f[I]value\f[R] is omitted (no \f[B]=\f[R]), the variable is set to
an empty string.
.TP
\f[B]\-u\f[R], \f[B]\[en]user\f[R] \f[I]username\f[R]
Run the daemon as \f[I]username\f[R].
Calls \f[B]setuid\f[R](2), \f[B]setgid\f[R](2), and
\f[B]initgroups\f[R](3), and sets the \f[B]USER\f[R], \f[B]HOME\f[R],
and \f[B]LOGNAME\f[R] environment variables.
Requires root privileges.
.TP
\f[B]\-v\f[R], \f[B]\[en]verbose\f[R]
Print diagnostic information to stderr before daemonizing.
.TP
\f[B]\-h\f[R], \f[B]\[en]help\f[R]
Print a help message and exit.
.TP
\f[B]\-V\f[R], \f[B]\[en]version\f[R]
Print version information and exit.
.SH EXIT STATUS
Exit codes follow the \f[B]sysexits.h\f[R] conventions:
.TP
\f[B]0\f[R]
Daemon started successfully.
.TP
\f[B]64\f[R] (EX_USAGE)
Configuration or validation error.
.TP
\f[B]66\f[R] (EX_NOINPUT)
Program not found or not executable.
.TP
\f[B]67\f[R] (EX_NOUSER)
User not found.
.TP
\f[B]69\f[R] (EX_UNAVAILABLE)
Lock file held by another process.
.TP
\f[B]71\f[R] (EX_OSERR)
OS error: fork, setsid, chdir, or exec failed.
.TP
\f[B]73\f[R] (EX_CANTCREAT)
Cannot create lock file, PID file, or output file.
.TP
\f[B]77\f[R] (EX_NOPERM)
Permission denied for user switch.
.SH EXAMPLES
Run a program as a daemon with a PID file:
.IP
.EX
daemonize \-p /var/run/myapp.pid \-\- /usr/bin/myapp \-\-config /etc/myapp.conf
.EE
.PP
Redirect output and run as a specific user:
.IP
.EX
daemonize \-p /var/run/myapp.pid \[rs]
          \-o /var/log/myapp/stdout.log \[rs]
          \-e /var/log/myapp/stderr.log \[rs]
          \-a \[rs]
          \-u myapp \[rs]
          \-\- /usr/bin/myapp
.EE
.PP
Prevent duplicate instances with a lock file:
.IP
.EX
daemonize \-p /var/run/myapp.pid \[rs]
          \-l /var/run/myapp.lock \[rs]
          \-\- /usr/bin/myapp
.EE
.PP
Set environment variables and working directory:
.IP
.EX
daemonize \-c /srv/myapp \[rs]
          \-E DATABASE_URL=postgres://localhost/myapp \[rs]
          \-E RUST_LOG=info \[rs]
          \-\- /usr/bin/myapp
.EE
.SH SEE ALSO
